\begin_layout Exercise
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Prove that if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\neq3$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}-2x+3\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 (Would this result be true if we took 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\neq3$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x=3+\delta$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\in\mathbb{R}-\left\{ 0\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 into the polynomial yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x^{2}-2x+3 & \neq0\\
\left(3+\delta\right)^{2}-2\left(3+\delta\right)+3 & \neq0\\
9+\delta^{2}+6\delta-2\delta-6+3 & \neq0\\
\delta^{2}+4\delta+6 & \neq0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The roots of the polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta^{2}+4\delta+6$
\end_inset

 are complex, which means 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall x\in\mathbb{R},x^{2}-2x+3\neq0$
\end_inset

, thus the statement is trivially true.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Prove that if 
\begin_inset Formula $2<n<3$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $7n+3$
\end_inset

 is odd.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $2<n<3$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 This premise is always false since there is no natural number in the open
 interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(2,3\right)$
\end_inset

, thus the statement is vacuously true.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
Prove that if 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is an odd integer, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}$
\end_inset

 is odd.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is an odd integer.
 This implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists k\in\mathbb{Z},x=2k+1$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x^{2} & =\left(2k+1\right)^{2}\\
 & =4k^{2}+4k+1\\
 & =2\left(2k^{2}+2k\right)+1\\
 & =2y+1,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}$
\end_inset

 is odd.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
Prove that if 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is an even integer, then 
\begin_inset Formula $7x-5$
\end_inset

 is odd.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is an even integer.
 This implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists k\in\mathbb{Z},x=2k$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
7x-5 & =7\left(2k\right)-5\\
 & =14k-5\\
 & =14k-6+1\\
 & =2\left(7k-3\right)+1\\
 & =2y+1,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathbb{Z}.$
\end_inset

 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $7x-5$
\end_inset

 is odd.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Prove that if 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 are odd, then 
\begin_inset Formula $ab+bc$
\end_inset

 is even.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 are odd.
 This implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $a=2k+1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c=2j+1$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k,j\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
ab+bc & =\left(2k+1\right)b+b\left(2j+1\right)\\
 & =b\left(2k+2j+2\right)\\
 & =2b\left(k+j+1\right)\\
 & =2y,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $y=b\left(k+j+1\right)\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $ab+bc$
\end_inset

 is even.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Prove that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|n\right|<1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $3n-2$
\end_inset

 is an even integer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|n\right|<1$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 in the only integer in the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(-1,1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

, the term 
\begin_inset Formula $3n-2$
\end_inset

 simplifies to 
\begin_inset Formula $-2$
\end_inset

 which can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $2\left(-1\right)$
\end_inset

 which is an even integer.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $3n-2$
\end_inset

 is an even integer if the premise holds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
Prove that every odd integer is a difference of two square integers.
 In other words, if 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is odd integer, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists y,z\in\mathbb{Z},x=y^{2}-z^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
By definition of being an odd integer, let 
\begin_inset Formula $x=2k+1$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Also let 
\begin_inset Formula $y=k+1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z=k$
\end_inset

.
 Substituting this into 
\begin_inset Formula $x=y^{2}-z^{2}$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
2k+1 & =\left(k+1\right)^{2}-k^{2}\\
 & =k^{2}+2k+1-k^{2}\\
 & =2k+1,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which shows that every odd integer is a difference of two square integers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Contrapositive
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Prove that if 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{2}+3$
\end_inset

 is odd, then 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is even.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We work this contrapositively.
 Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is odd so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists k\in\mathbb{Z},a=2k+1$
\end_inset

, and substitute the expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{2}+3$
\end_inset

 to get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
a^{2}+3 & =\left(2k+1\right)^{2}+3\\
 & =4k^{2}+4k+1+3\\
 & =2\left(2k^{2}+2k+2\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which shows that it is even.
 Thus if 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{2}+3$
\end_inset

 is odd, then 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is even.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
Prove the following: Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $xy+y^{2}$
\end_inset

 is even, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is odd or 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is even.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We work this contrapositively by proving when 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is even and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is odd, then 
\begin_inset Formula $xy+y^{2}$
\end_inset

 is odd.
 The integers 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $x=2k$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y=2j+1$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k,j\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Substituting in these expressions for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $xy+y^{2}$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
xy+y^{2} & =2k\left(2j+1\right)+\left(2j+1\right)^{2}\\
 & =2kj+2k+4j^{2}+2j+1\\
 & =2\left(kj+k+2j^{2}+j\right)+1\\
 & =2n+1,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $n=kj+k+2j^{2}+j\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus showing that 
\begin_inset Formula $xy+y^{2}$
\end_inset

 is odd when 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is even and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is odd.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is odd if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{3}$
\end_inset

 is odd.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We begin by showing that if 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is odd then 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{3}$
\end_inset

 is odd.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is odd, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists k\in\mathbb{Z},s=2k+1$
\end_inset

.
 Substituting this into 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{3}$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
s^{3} & =\left(2k+1\right)^{3}\\
 & =\left(4k^{2}+4k+1\right)\left(2k+1\right)\\
 & =8k^{3}+4k^{2}+8k^{2}+4k+2k+1\\
 & =8k^{3}+12k^{2}+6k+1\\
 & =2\left(4k^{2}+6k^{2}+3k\right)+1,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which is odd.
 Next we show that if 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{3}$
\end_inset

 is odd, then 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is odd.
 We work this contrapositively by proving that if 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is even then 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{3}$
\end_inset

 is even.
 The integer 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $s=2j$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $j\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Substituting this into the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{3}$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
s^{3} & =\left(2j\right)^{3}\\
 & =8j^{3}\\
 & =2\left(4j^{3}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{3}$
\end_inset

 is an even number.
 Thus if 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{3}$
\end_inset

 is odd, then 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is odd.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
Consider the following situation.
 A student is asked to prove the statement: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Given 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $2\mid x$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is even.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 The student writes: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Assume, contrapositively, that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is even.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $x=2k$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $2\mid x$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Identify what is wrong with this students proof and write a correct proof.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
When proving the implication 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in S,P\left(x\right)\implies Q\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 contrapositively, we are proving the implication 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in S,\neg Q\left(x\right)\implies\neg P\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The student didn't negate the premise 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 when writing the proof.
 This proof can easily be proven using a direct or contrapositive approach.
 We will prove it directly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $2\mid x$
\end_inset

 which by definition means that 
\begin_inset Formula $x=2k$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 which is the definition of an integer being even.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c,d\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Prove that if 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mid c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b\mid d$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $ab\mid cd$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mid c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b\mid d$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $c=ak$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d=bj$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k,j\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Using these definitions in the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $ab\mid cd$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
ab\mid cd & =ab\mid akbj\\
 & =ab\mid abkj.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

By definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $ab\mid abjk$
\end_inset

 we get 
\begin_inset Formula $abjk=abm$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, which reduces to 
\begin_inset Formula $jk=m$
\end_inset

.
 Thus proving that if 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mid c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b\mid d$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $ab\mid cd$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
State the contrapositive of the implication in the previous exercise.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c,d\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $ab\nmid cd$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $a\nmid c$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $b\nmid d$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Prove that if 
\begin_inset Formula $4\nmid a^{2}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is odd.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We prove this contrapositively by showing that if 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is even, then 
\begin_inset Formula $4\mid a^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Assuming that 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is even, we can write it as 
\begin_inset Formula $a=2k$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Substituting this into the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $4\mid a^{2}$
\end_inset

 yields
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
4\mid a^{2} & =4\mid4k^{2},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

 is a divisor of 
\begin_inset Formula $4k^{2}$
\end_inset

;therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

 is a divisor of 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
Prove the following implication two ways (directly and contrapositively):
 Given 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $5x-1$
\end_inset

 is even only if 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is odd.
 In other words 
\begin_inset Formula $5x-1\text{ is even}\implies x\text{ is odd}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
(Direct)
\series default
 We assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $5x-1$
\end_inset

 is even which means 
\begin_inset Formula $5x-1=2j$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $j\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $j=5k+2$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, then we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
5x-1 & =2j\\
 & =2\left(5k+2\right)\\
 & =10k+4,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $5x$
\end_inset

 gives us 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
5x=10k+5.
\]

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $5\mid10k+5$
\end_inset

, we can solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and get the solution 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=2k+1,
\]

\end_inset

which shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is an odd integer.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout --Separator--

\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
(Contrapositively)
\series default
 We prove this contrapositively by showing that if 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is even then 
\begin_inset Formula $5x-1$
\end_inset

 is odd.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is even, it can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $x=2k$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Substituting this into the term 
\begin_inset Formula $5x-1$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
5x-1 & =5\left(2k\right)-1\\
 & =10k-1\\
 & =2\left(5k\right)-1\\
 & =2\left(5k\right)-1-2+2\\
 & =2\left(5k-1\right)+1\\
 & =2y+1,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $y=5k-1\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $5x-1$
\end_inset

 is odd if 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is even.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
When I say we in the proofs, I really mean I.
 I am just use to saying we when writing papers.
\end_layout

